ons in order to establish their identity. Liminality continued to find new contexts, referring to concepts such as borders, the space between two countries, twilight, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; the time between day and night, and architecture, space designed to transition between two rooms. So, in the most general sense, we can think of liminality as a state of betweenness, not quite one reality or another. That's why it's disorienting. Persons twice the spectrum of liminal spaces. &gt;&gt; I think in the true sense would typically be like connective tissue locations, so like anywhere that's not a final destination, like a living room. You might have some trouble classifying as liminal space unless it's like the living room on the last day you were in your childhood house before you're moving out. The liminality can come from a few different vectors. &gt;&gt; And liminal spaces have existed in a wide variety of media, from the work of surrealists like Salvador Dali to video games like Portal and Half-Life. Liminal spaces also have an aesthetic quality that stretches beyond the strict definition of liminality. What exactly makes a liminal space look [music] liminal? And how can filmmakers emphasize that liminality? Some have argued that the root of the liminal space aesthetic is an uncanniness. Something looks familiar, but feels off. In this paper from the Journal of Environmental Psychology, Alexander Diel identified six common factors that make spaces feel liminal. The first is lack, which Diel explains as rooms lacking expected or essential features like specific furniture, doors/windows, or completely empty rooms. Some of the most off-putting settings [music] in David Lynch's Twin Peaks The Return are the empty homes in the suburbs of Las Vegas. They feel strange simply because they are lacking any furnishing we would expect in these spaces. The minimalist monotone color grade further emphasizes the sense of lack. &gt;&gt; Oh my god, Dougie, what the hell? Where'