 charge. When light hits these [music] capacitors, they act as individual photosites. The charge in these photosites is then transferred through the sensor's grid, allowing for high image quality, [music] since each pixel has to use the same pathway to output its signal. But this process is very power intensive, especially compared to the CMOS [music] sensor. CMOS sensors differ from CCDs by containing multiple transistors at each photosite, rather than having [music] to transfer the charges across the sensor grid. This has several perks. It's more energy efficient, can read charges more quickly, and has a similar structure to computer microprocessors. Meaning they can be built at lower costs, and can incorporate functions like noise reduction and image processing [music] within the sensor. Today, CMOS sensors dominate filmmaking. They're cheaper, have faster readouts, perform better in low-light, and are more flexible overall. CCDs are largely obsolete, but they can have a distinctive more analog-style look, which could [music] fit your project's aesthetic. Sensors are also differentiated by either a global shutter or a rolling shutter. A global shutter refers to when a sensor takes in the entire area of an image simultaneously. A rolling shutter, meanwhile, is when a sensor scans an image sequentially. Rolling shutters can result in undesirable artifacts, especially with quick movement, where individual elements get skewed due to the sequential [music] intake. There are also some downsides to global shutters. They can often have more digital noise and a narrower dynamic range and can run hotter. Some global shutters overcome these drawbacks, but that means they are typically more expensive. With that out of the way, let's look at [music] some common sensor sizes. In the world of camera sensors, there are some used primarily in photography, while others are used in digital filmmaking. At the top is the large format sensor. This is a broad category that covers any sensor larger than photography's full frame and cinematography's Super 35. Cinema cameras, like the Alexa 65, [music] have large format sensors measuring 54.12 by 25.58 mm. And Blackmagic's URSA Cine 17K 65 at 51 by 24 mm. The Alexa 65 has been used on many of the biggest films, including Barbie, Furiosa, and Project Hail Mary. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Slightly smaller are medium format sensors, but they are more often used in photography. They are generally 44 by 33 mm. These sensors have extremely high image quality and especially impressive low-light performance. But these perks come at a high price point. In photography, one of the most common sensor sizes is the full frame. These are 36 by 24 [music] mm sensors. Being a larger sensor, they too have high image quality and solid low-light performance, as well as a relatively wide dynamic range. In cinematography, one of the most common sensors [music] is the Super 35 mm. These measure approximately 24.89 by 18.66 mm. Super 35 became the standard in cinema for decades, and many of today's most popular digital cinema cameras still use it. Films such as Bad Boys: Ride or Die, Air, and The Minecraft Movie were all shot with the Alexa 35 camera. &gt;&gt; [screaming] &gt;&gt; Chicken Jockey. &gt;&gt; The slightly smaller APS-C sensor is mostly used in photography, and actual sizes vary, but the most common is 23.6 by 15.6 mm. Their smaller size means they capture less light than their full-frame counterparts, and have some crop factor. Micro 4/3 sensors are even smaller, with an average size of 17.3 by 13 mm. They still have a strong image quality, but they do less well in low light, and have a much more significant two times crop factor. 1-in sensors are typically found in compact cameras like the ones in smartphones or drones. The common size for these sensors is 13.2 by 8.8 mm. These are limited to small focal lengths, lack the resolution of larger sensors, and have a 2.7 times crop factor. When choosing between these sensor options, ask yourself what you're hoping to get out of your shoot. Each sensor is different, and there are a lot of variables at play, but in general, larger sensors do better in low light conditions, have a wider dynamic range, and allow for a shallower depth of field and a greater field of view. Where smaller sensors might lack in these areas, they make up for it in cost savings, portability, deeper focus, and lighter lenses. Let's look more closely at these sensors qualities. Different sensor sizes have different strengths and weaknesses and can affect image quality in a multitude of ways. The first is depth of field. Larger sensors create shallower depth of field than their smaller counterparts, but only when framing and exposure are matched. This makes large sensor photography popular among filmmakers desiring a cinematic shallow focus look. For a more run-and-gun [music] project, however, a deeper depth of field may be more useful, and therefore a smaller sensor can be handy. Field of view is another consideration. Larger sensors capture more of the image that is projected by a lens. For example, a 35-mm lens on a full-frame camera will provide a significantly wider shot than the same lens on a micro 4/3 sensor. This phenomenon is described as a crop factor, which tells you how much a smaller sensor crops into an image. Crop factor doesn't change a lens itself. It only changes how much [music] of its image is captured. It should be noted, however, that there are lenses specifically designed for smaller sensors. An MFT sensor doesn't crop the image provided by an MFT lens, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; for example. Sensor size can also affect low-light capabilities and dynamic range. Say a larger sensor has the same effective megapixel count as a smaller sensor. This means that it has larger photosites, which are able to capture more light than the photosites of the smaller sensor. Therefore, larger sensors often perform better in low light, which in turn helps to expand their dynamic range. Other factors, like sensor design, processing, and bit depth, also play a role in determining dynamic range. Another variable to consider when selecting a sensor is its noise, which refers to the graininess that appears in images, especially at higher ISOs. Noise can come from a variety of factors, such as the sensor circuitry design and sensitivity. In practice, lenses, lighting, and composition often have a bigger impact in your image than sensor size alone. Regardless of the project, cinematography is an art form that requires attention to detail. And nowhere is this more true than when picking a sensor. The difference in a few millimeters can be all the difference in the world. &gt;&gt; [cheering] &gt;&gt; Before you start camera shopping, plan out what you're going to shoot with StudioBinder's pre-production software, which includes apps for shot listing, storyboarding, [music] and more. That's all for now. Remember, a great shot is a great shot, no matter the sensor size. &gt;&gt; [music] [music]

